<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Living Streets Response to the Transport Select Committee inquiry on winter resilience in transport</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from Living Streets (WRT 007)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are the national charity that stands up for pedestrians. With our supporters we work to create safe,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> attractive and enjoyable streets, where people want to walk. We work with communities, professionals and politicians to make sure every community can enjoy vibrant streets and public spaces.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We started life in 1929 as the Pedestrians Association and have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">en the national voice for pedestrians throughout our history. In the early years, our campaigning led to the introduction of the driving test, pedestrian crossings and 30 mph speed limits. Since then our ambition has grown. Today we influence decision m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">akers nationally and locally, run successful projects to encourage people to walk and provide specialist consultancy services to help reduce congestion and carbon emissions, improve public health, and make sure every community can enjoy the benefits of wal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">king.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Background</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Living Street believes pedestrian safety is just as important as preventing road traffic accidents. Clearing pavements and paths serving key local destinations should be given the same priority as key roads in relevant plans and winter </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">maintenance schedules.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Research undertaken by YouGov on behalf of Living Streets during the winter of 2012/2013 revealed that 65% of people agree and strongly agree that their councils could do more to keep pavements clear of snow and ice. Furthermore, ov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er 54% of the population have fallen on an icy pavement and 55% of respondents have been injured by a fall on an icy pavement or they know someone who has (22% have been injured and 33% know someone who has been injured from a fall). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Impact on pedestrian</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">s</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">During times of severe winter weather trips and falls on icy pavements can have a serious impact on pedestrians – especially the elderly – and also significant costs to the economy in terms of health care. This is before any consideration of the physical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and emotional impact of injuries. There were over 16,000 emergency hospital admissions in England due to falls on snow and ice during the winter of 2009/10 costing an estimated £42 million. The following winter 14,300 admissions were recorded involving fa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lls on ice and snow.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Walking around local neighbourhoods is vital to maintain good physical and mental health into old age. Age UK has found that going for walks is the second most popular and pleasurable activity among older people. Furthermore, their Pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ide of Place campaign estimated that the cost of an older person losing their independence and going into residential care costs the tax payer £18,000. Concerns over the risk of such injuries can prevent older people going out during periods of severe weat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">her leading to increased isolation and loneliness. Anecdotal evidence from our projects has revealed that many older will not risk going out when it is icy and, therefore, can severely limits their social interaction for sustained periods. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On a related </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">point it is important to recognise that where older people struggle to heat their home during winter, cold homes can increase the risk of trips and falls outside </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">because symptoms of arthritis become worse in cold or damp homes, strength and dexterity decre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ase as temperatures drop, increasing the risk of falls or injuries.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Solutions</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local councils have the power and duty to ensure ice free pavements for pedestrians. As such we believe every local authority should, as a minimum, make sure:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a severe weather </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">plan is in place that sets out what the council will do to reduce the impact of severe weather on all road users – including pedestrians</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">paths are gritted so that everyone (including older, younger and disabled people) is still able to walk to essential se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rvices</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">staff and contractors are sent to help clear pavements if they are unable to carry out their main job because of the severe weather</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all grit bins are kept full so that grit can be used where it is needed</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many local authorities are in a position to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deliver our calls.  An LGA survey of local authorities in England and Wales (October 2012) found that:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">20% of councils have more salt than the previous year; 69% the same. 97% have all the supplies they ordered;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Over the past year, 39% had bought new gritt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ers, 27% new mini-gritters and 17% other equipment such as ploughs, footway gritters, tractors, snow-blowers and quad bikes;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">59% of councils will be supplying salt and equipment to parish councils, community groups or snow wardens, and 35% are working with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local farmers and 4x4 owners to help in the effort. 76% of councils will be placing community grit bins for residents to use on side streets;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">78% of councils will be providing live updates to residents on weather, gritting activity and services. 98% of th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ese will have a dedicated resource on their website, 76% will be using a Twitter feed and 33% a Facebook page.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst we are aware of many local authorities adopting good practice in relation to tackling icy pavements through winter weather contracts much</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> more still needs to be done to ensure pedestrian routes are given the same priority as routes for motor vehicles and to share good practice. Living Streets research revealed that whilst 71% of people were aware of main roads being gritted for vehicles in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">their area yet previous research undertaken by the charity Independent Age found that 15% of UK adults are aware of councils gritting pavements in priority areas such as care homes and schools, and only 9% had seen evidence of action to keep other pavement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s in their area clear.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Living Streets also believes councils could do more to help organise teams of volunteer snow wardens. Research from Independent Age reveals that only 26% of people are aware of local residents clearing pavements in their area and only two per cent have see</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n the volunteer snow wardens which some councils have recruited to help clear ice and snow from streets. However, our research suggests there is high degree of 'community spirit' during times of severe when people are likely to clear the street of ice and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">snow outside their or their neighbour's home. Our research revealed that 42% of people would volunteer to help clear snow and ice from the pavements in their local area with particularly high levels of agreement from those aged 25-34 (49%) and aged 35-44 (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">50%) responded positively – this shows community spirit.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Central Government also has a key role in maintaining a constant consistent message to the general public that they are very unlikely to get sued for clearing the pavement of snow and ice. The DCLG </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">guidance on community during severe welcome clearly spells out that 'you can help clear paths and pavements to prevent slips and fall - don't believe the myths about being sued'. It is vital the Government continues to reinforce this guidance through commu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nications and public awareness campaigns on a yearly basis during the winter months.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Finally, following the move of public health back into local authorities we believe there is more opportunity to utilise public health funds to increase the amount of gri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tting which takes place during periods of adverse winter weather in order to keep pedestrian routes clear of snow and ice and reduce the number of hospital admissions from slips and falls. However, it is vital that any such funding is used to enhance servi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce provision as opposed to funding core gritting services.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>